<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Old Vine Zinfandel and regular Zinfandel?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Old Vine Zinfandel comes from vines typically 50+ years old, producing more concentrated, complex wines with deeper fruit flavors and better structure. These older vines naturally yield smaller crops, resulting in wines with more intensity and character compared to younger vine Zinfandels. Look for producers like Ravenswood, Turley, or Ridge who specialize in old vine bottlings for the most authentic expression.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I choose California Zinfandel or Italian Primitivo?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">California Zinfandel typically offers bolder, more fruit-forward flavors with higher alcohol (14-16%), while Italian Primitivo tends to be more restrained with earthy, mineral notes and moderate alcohol (13-14%). California versions excel with BBQ and bold flavors, whereas Primitivo pairs better with Mediterranean cuisine and lighter dishes. Both are genetically identical grapes but express terroir differently.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What food pairings work best with premium Zinfandel?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The best Zinfandels shine with grilled meats, especially lamb, beef brisket, and spicy sausages, as their bold fruit and spice notes complement smoky, charred flavors. The wine's natural acidity and tannins also make it excellent with rich tomato-based dishes, aged cheeses like sharp cheddar, and dark chocolate desserts. Avoid delicate fish or light salads, as Zinfandel's intensity can overpower subtle flavors.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I identify a high-quality Zinfandel worth the investment?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for balanced alcohol levels (14.5-15.5% rather than 16%+), which indicates restrained winemaking and better food compatibility. Quality Zinfandels should show clear varietal character with blackberry and spice notes, firm but not harsh tannins, and good acidity for structure. Check for single-vineyard designations or "old vine" labels from respected producers like Ridge, Turley, or Seghesio, which typically indicate higher quality fruit sources.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Zinfandel a good wine for beginners to explore?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Zinfandel can be excellent for beginners due to its approachable fruit-forward character and food-friendly nature, but start with balanced examples rather than high-alcohol "fruit bombs." Look for producers like Bogle, Cline, or Ravenswood's entry-level bottlings that offer typical Zinfandel character without excessive alcohol or oak. The grape's natural spice and berry flavors make it easy to understand and enjoy while learning about wine.</p>
